segments.text: And so he was easily aggravated.
And so a student says, Doc, Dr. Lindsay, should we drive our cars or some detail?
Doc said, that's a detail.
Then another one shows up his hand, and he says, ask him a similar type question.
I told you that's a detail.
And that went on, and then he just went, after a while he just turned around and took off.
And they said, what happened?
The students asked me, what happened to him?
But he was, I remember that real clearly.
Did any student ever try to play a joke or a prank on you as a teacher?
I don't know that they did.
No.
I think one time we may have left somebody in the classroom asleep, you know, after class or something like that.
Did any student ever try to bribe you for a grade or anything like that?
No.
No.
A lot of them coming around trying to get grades raised.
That's a common occurrence.
I'll tell you one of the things that you might enjoy was when we first let girls in.
Old Dick Davidson over there was counseling one of them, and I happened to walk by the door.
An old girl was just sitting there just boo-hooing.
And Dr. Davidson looked over and said, Here comes Dr. Holland.
He'll help you.
He was ready to unload that girl.
Did you ever have a parent or any other outsider try to twist your arm on anything?
Yeah, I had one student, but he got over it.
He thought his little brother was sharper than he was, and we hadn't placed him high enough or something, giving him a,
tough enough courses, and it turned out he couldn't even handle what he had.
The only problem I had a little, I had the only problem with two or three profs, young ones that we hired.
We hired one guy from
He had gone to Switzerland.
What's the capital of that place?
Bern.
Bern, Lucerne, Geneva, Lausanne.
I've forgotten which one it was right now.
I don't think we've hit it.
Anyway, it's a well-known university.
And every one of them that we got out of there, they handled their students just so rough that the students couldn't get along with them.
And the students couldn't get along with this fellow.
And so we had to let him go.
And since then, he got an appointment over there.
And he makes a point to always send me a card.
We had another boy, young man, that we got.
Came to us from MIT, just as sharp as he could be.
And you could write a wonderful letter.
But his, and when you talk to him, you'd think, this guy is just going to make an outstanding faculty member.
I hired him.
Well, Toby said, you know, that's the first guy that we've had that got into a squabble with everybody in the entire department, including all the mechanics downstairs, in less than one month.
And we had to finally...
let him go, and I got him a job with Bell Labs.
I said, you people can handle somebody like this.
I can't handle him because he's just too overbearing.
He needs a job where he put him over in a corner.
Another one I'll tell you is Bokris.
I had the opportunity, the first opportunity, to hire him.
He came in over there to get me to hire him, and I had this young faculty that I had just hired.
Most of them were 10 or 15 years younger than I was.
And he came in there, and he had a list of books that were longer than most anybody's list of papers.
I said, how in the world do you do that?
He said, well, I just kind of sketch out a few things, and I get somebody else fill in those little details.
But I could just tell that guy was so overbearing.
And I decided that I didn't care how good he was, that I had to think of the fact that I had nine or 10 other faculty there.
that I wanted to develop.
And if I had somebody like that, he would just try to intimidate them and run all over them.
And so I declined hiring him.
I didn't care how good he was.
You've got to look at this thing.
Are you big enough to hire somebody like that?
If you're real big, you can handle them.
But if you're no bigger than we were, you just can't handle somebody that's, I don't care how good he is.
Well, old Martel hired him.
And I saw Martel later, and he said to me, he says, how in the world did you pass up that man?
I said, well, I decided we couldn't work with him over there.
So I'm not sure what he says now.
But anyway, I missed my opportunity there.
Let's see, one of the people I forgot to ask about, and if we, this is a note to the typist that moved this back up to where we were talking about other administrators, Dick Winerdi.
Oh, he was really a good one.
Dick...
I gave him a departmental position as professor because he couldn't get anybody else to take him on.
He wanted to teach this little course in activation analysis.
So I made him a professor of chemical engineering.
And he was over in the dean's office all the time.
And so after he went with Calhoun,
I've forgotten.
He jumped me about something.
I wrote some letter to him that just really had a twist in it.
And I sent a copy of it to Fred.
And he called me up and he said, boy, that just tickled the life out of me.
He said, but you know, I don't understand Wayne Erdy.
When he was working for me, I just didn't have any problem with him, but he's giving me a lot of problems now.
And he said, I can't understand that.
And I said, well, what the problem is now?
He used to be working for you.
He's working for John Gavilan now.
But the funny one was that when he got two different occasions, when...
He was already out in the industry, and he called me.
You can tell what's coming.
He says, Charlie, being on the department staff of chemical engineering was one of the highest honors that I've ever had.
I said, my boy wants to get into graduate school.
Could you help me?
Then another one was whenever he finally got crosswise over there and he was looking for a home, I thought we were going to get him back because he was on my faculty.
And so he was calling up wanting to come back.
That's right, when Dr. Miller became president.
He'd been crosswise with some of those.
See, Dick and I had offices that adjoined each other, and the first three days that Dr. Miller was president, he didn't even say good morning to Dick.
He literally did not say a word to him.
Dick came into my office and said to me tersely, he said, I've got to find some work somewhere.
Well, he called me, and I told him, well, you know, we'll try to use you.
Come on over, because I knew we were obligated to.
Now, when he was working for Dean Benson, what was his task?
When he was still in engineering, what was his task?
Oh, I think he had him doing, Fred put more stock in what he told him than I would have.
He kind of had Fred buffaloed a little bit.
Fred would kind of fall for some of that.
Was he to try to bring in research money?
Well, he was involved in a lot of the, it was more in research than anything else.
But he got stuck on him and Newell both.
And I could tell Newell was no good the day that he came in when he was looking for a job.
And I made a couple suggestions to him, and he just brushed them off.
And I could tell that he wasn't going to make it.
But Fred did.
go along with him quite a while.
He was subject to being sucked in a little bit.
Wayne Erdy had that activation analysis.
He didn't have it down where he could, I've forgotten, Paul Crawford used to laugh about.
He was looking, he had his system fixed so he could shove these samples kind of like J.C. Penney's all over the place.
but he couldn't find silicon in carborundum, which is made out of silicon.
He got in a cart for the horse.
Back to...
Joyous pleasures of being the department head.
What are some other achievements that you remember during those years that you're proud to look back on?
You said teaching was the biggest.
Well, I've got a lot of books published.
I've got seven books published, and I've got a lot of them in distillation, kinetics, catalysis.
In 93, I wrote one on quantitative cancer modeling and risk assessment with Silken, who's a statistician.
And so I enjoy very much the development of ideas on paper.
And see, when I became department head, I realized that I didn't have time to be down in that lab working all the time.
I just couldn't do it.
And so what I did do was get into this other field, and I got started with Exxon down there in 1955 because I had, from a master's degree, had worked with Phil Murdoch on...

on algebraic solution of very simple distillation problems and there's just three or four components and I got down there and OB Franklin said well since you're an expert on distillation we're going to let you work out this uh... this big old tower uh... pipe still and it had about thirty forty plates and probably five hundred components and uh... streams going off everywhere and actually
In the way we were looking at them, when you're doing finite differences, every time you come to a terminal condition, you've got another set of boundary conditions.
So they gave me that problem.
And I just walked around for about two weeks
trying to figure out how in the world, I can't even solve that little one.
How in the world can I solve anything like this?
So I finally found out a way to do it, and that's what got me started on all this other stuff.
And they eventually were the first ones to develop a program on it, which we call the theta method.
And it is still a real good method, and it has some theoretical basis.
And then I wrote a book on kinetics,
And it's still being used over there.
The one on kinetics is used, and also we're using the one on distillation.
So those two books are still in use.
What were your guidelines for being a good department head?
Oh, I don't know.
I just tried to treat everybody fair.
That was all.
Just kind of treat them like you'd like to be treated yourself.
As near as you can.
And it's hard to do that, but to not have any, uh, be favoritism over one or the other.
Try to have an open door to any of them that had any problem.
And, uh,
and have some concern, it's very difficult, but that's what I tried to do, and tried to help them as much as I could with what helped them advance their own careers.
And you obviously had some graduate students.
Which are the graduate students you're most proud to claim?
Let's see, there are several of them that have done real well.
Norman Tetlow was one of them who went to Dow that developed the whole design package for them.
And Ron McDaniel was also with him down there.
And then Narker, I don't know, he was a graduate student, worked over at the center some.
Another good one.
I've had a lot of good graduate students.

so and some of them very very good in fact I had two Dan Taylor and Park Davis that both went to Rice and I got them as graduate students and they also worked with took some courses under Dr. Kleppel he said that they were two of the best mathematical minds that he had seen come through from engineering that they just
they could handle it, and they were good students.
With what other institutions did you most closely cooperate?

Oh, I did some with the University of Texas, but not anything in real detail, but Ben Winkle over there was, he worked in distillation, but he did more of the experimental work, and I was, I'd gotten off into the other design, it's really design methods, I'd gotten into that because
That's all a department head's got time to do.

And also with Bill Akers down at Rice, you may have known of him, he was, he went to Tech and later went on and got his degree at Rice and stayed down there with the administration for a good long while.
As the enrollment at A&M began to change, women were admitted, corps became volunteer and so forth, did that, how did that affect the department?
The only thing that affected us was whenever the enrollment got away, and we just were looking at the possibility of having to run labs night and day and all that kind of thing.
That was the only thing, and that kind of came to an end, and we didn't have the space for it.
But other than that, I'd say that over the years that the students, I think they've really gotten better.
I've got a real excellent class right now,
I remember when I first started teaching, there was a tendency for students to think, well, by the time we get to be seniors, we've already got the fundamental knowledge.
All we're gonna do from here on is think.

solve problems but they didn't have it all and then if you gave them something new and said well we haven't had that you know as if that weren't fair territory but the students now just take it anything comes out of them.
Do you think that the courses that you and your colleagues teach now are more demanding
Oh, yeah, they are.
And they're higher quality.
Actually, I was disappointed when I got my degree in chemical engineering because I'd had a pretty good background in mathematics and science, and they weren't using it.
They were just using mainly arithmetic.
And they made it hard, but just giving you catchy problems.
That's why they kept the grades down.
But the material they really covered wasn't really all that hard, the fundamentals.

Another thing we had was open book, which encouraged you not to do anything, which is not near as good as thinking that you're going to have to go in there and have it all in your mind so that you can spend your time working the problem instead of thumbing through the book.
And when you give open book quizzes, what happens is that you give something they can't find in there anyway.
And so I think it's better.
After that, I never did give open book quizzes.
I just felt like that.
You can, students will do better if they have to, there's certain tools that you're gonna have to learn regardless, and just well learn them.

It may be drudgery, but there's certain, a carpenter's got to have a hammer and a saw, and if you're gonna do any good, you need certain fundamentals that you understand thoroughly, and you don't have to be looking them up.
As women began to be in the classroom, did y'all have any examples of where somebody forgot that he was speaking now to a mixed audience and said something?
I don't know, but I got one of these reports back once, and I could never figure out what I had done that was sexy or something.
And that baffled me.
I've never been called on it but once, but I don't know what it was.
It must have been somebody gave a poor grade, because I've never been called on it before.
And I never tell anything in class that's off color.
The only thing that I did tell, I did show them a film that I had, some slides that I had made.
And that might have been, that's the only thing I could figure.
I was teaching a course on quantitative cancer modeling and risk assessment.
And going back, and I was giving a little bit on waste disposal.
The first garbage disposal place was right outside of Jerusalem.
It's the Greek name now that's for hell.
It means the same thing, it was a mess.
And that was one of the things I pointed out.
But before I did that, I went back and pointed out that probably hazardous waste incineration or incineration began about 500,000 years ago.
And what I had was I got somebody to draw me this cartoon, and it showed these women were lugging the wood, throwing it on the fire, and the men were all sitting back watching them.
And I said, boy, in those days, men had it made.
And that's the only thing that I can figure out that I might have said that I never did know what it was.
In general, I'll tell you, the girls, what will happen is only the good ones will stay in.
The poor ones that see they can't make it, they're not like the boys.
The poor ones will drop out and go take another major.
You've got some boys that will stay in there until the bitter end.
And that's the difference you see.
Usually the girls are near the top of the class.
As far as you and your colleagues knew, was chemical engineering one of the most demanding majors on the campus?
Well, I think electrical was real demanding.
I think chemical, electrical, and mechanical was fairly demanding.
Those three were pretty demanding.
I'd say electrical may be.
Electrical and chemical were probably two of the most demanding, and I don't know.
I imagine it would depend on your aptitude as to which you would think would be the most demanding.
That reminds me to go way back to the early 60s again.

As you and I and others were part of that committee recommending the new name for this institution, did you and your colleagues in engineering have a preference for what the name ought to be or ought not to be?
You know, I haven't thought about it since then.
No, I don't really.
I don't know that at that time that we would have gone with Texas A&M University, though.
As I understand from Vice President, then Vice President Hall, he said that Mr. Rutter could not at all accept losing the A&M.
And that our committee, you remember, recommended Texas State University.
Because everybody else was going that way.
And he said Mr. Rutter just didn't like that at all.
And Dr. Hall said he's the one that came up with what it now is, the A&M with no periods and so forth.
And
As I look back, okay, everybody knows what school it is.
It doesn't mean that anymore.
No, that's right.
So I think it was a good deal going there.
That's what I'm saying, is it doesn't hurt to be different.
Right.
When did we begin to get large numbers of international students in engineering?
Well, we started getting them way back there in the 60s some, and I would not, I was trying to, at one time, we had some pressure on us to not have more than 30% in engineering graduate students.
And I kept mine down.
And I tried to keep them down.
We could have had a bigger class of graduate students.

And one of the things that we did to try to attract others was take these that had finished with a four-year degree in science from some of these teaching colleges and get them in, give them a fast course.
But that's when it started.
And now there's just probably no holes barred.
You can have any number you want to.
There was some concern that the legislature would be concerned about us educating so many foreign students.
And that prevailed a long time through engineering over there.
And we did keep ours down.
What would be your evaluation of the quality of the international students, the academic ability?
Oh, I think they're good.

But another thing that I think is that they are going to be the leaders unless we, I think that we might want to give some favoritism to ours, because what's happening to our own students now is that they can get a good salary when they get the BS degree, so they're going out and taking that job.

And I'm not so sure about what, there's nothing wrong with being, showing favoritism over your own national people that we shouldn't be able to give ours enough stipend more to attract a lot of good American students because they're the ones, a lot of those are gonna end up as director of your research, head of your chemical engineering departments throughout the country.
And so we ought to be doing more to attract those people.

and uh that it is we all have them all on the same part and generally that's correct if they're all citizens but if they're not citizens we don't have to do that and i think for our own good we need to we need to get some that are some of our own in in line all right i've now just anointed you as the advisor
to chemical engineering, planning the future, and then to engineering.
What advice would you give to your department and to your college colleagues as they look to the future?
Well, we did a big study, and I had all industry helping me on this.
And one of the things that we came up with was what they needed to start looking at was to make sure that these students have a better, rounded education.
Chemistry are only taking about 10 hours.
Above the bachelor for the PhD, the classroom is one of the best places to pick up and to learn another discipline.
And what we need is people that are broadly trained, and they can even have some business.
And this is not giving up the English and this sort of stuff.
I had a guy that taught me British prose and anthology.
And he at one time taught mathematics, and he said, I told Dr. Moore, who was president at that time, that I could not teach mathematics anymore because I started reading that poem.
And the Assyrians swept down.
He said, that just took me.
But I think they should be...
The classic, the well-educated man today really should be one that has some experience in the mathematics and the sciences and English.
And I think that's college-wide.
But also, he should have some...
some in the arts and sciences so that he knows where everything came from, the history of all of it.
And what I think we need to do is get back to having

chemical engineering students take their math in the math department and get them interested in teaching some courses that are not all just theoretical mathematics but some applied mathematics for the engineers, the chemists, and all these other people.
You should be taking courses and we should have some students taking some courses in physics and mathematics and

And we don't do that because what is going to happen, and even business, because what's going to happen is that things are changing so fast that you don't have time for somebody to come up on the curve anymore.
You've got to have people well enough, broad enough trained that we can go from one project to another and he still doesn't have such a long learning curve.
And I think that this was their feeling, that we've been going in the wrong direction.
And right now the legislature is still trying to make you take fewer hours and everything.
The best place to learn something is in the classroom.
It's the most efficient way.
And that's what I would say is let's turn out some really well-educated, well-rounded that have had some courses in all these other departments.
So that, and it's not just in engineering, it's all in the arts and sciences.
And I enjoyed, look back over it, I enjoyed some of those courses that I had outside the department far more than I did some of them I had inside.
The one I had in British prosanthology, I wouldn't take anything for that course.
And it depends on the teachers.
You've got to have real good teachers dedicated to teach those courses.
And so that's what I would, that's what it's going to take because what they've come up with the concept is that we are now in the age of a learning society.
And the B1 and most nations are going to adopt this concept because they found out that's the only way that they can
keep the competitive edge on their competitors or stay ahead of them is by learning technology faster than they do.
And to learn it faster, you've got to have a broad background so you can switch from one technology to another and pick it up.
And so I would say that that would be, they'd all be well served to start looking at teaching more courses and over a broader scope.
But now none of these students take courses outside.
I mentioned already to you how many I took outside the department.
Then I went over after I got my PhD and took all the courses that they offered in the math department on top of it.
So this is the direction we ought to go in so that they can switch fields.
See, I wrote this book on quantitative cancer model and risk assessment statistics.
And I never had a course in it, but I had enough mathematics
that I could work with silken and try to figure it out, but I wrote it so that engineers could read it.
In terms of the department's leadership, should it be a department head or a department chairman?
Oh, I think a department head, I think you need more of a line organization.

And I'm not sure that the terms ought to be so limited because if you get to putting so much emphasis on just being a professor and doing research, the guy says, hell, I'll take it for four years and I'm not going to bust my butt because it's not going to have anything to do with where I'm going.
I'll take it and get mine done and then somebody else can have it.
I think that's a tendency in chairmanships.
And I was using the term chairman also to mean that the chairman is bound by the majority vote.
Yeah.
I don't think that's a good way to run it.
I usually would try to, every once in a while you're not going to
Well, first of all, you should be convincing people that this is the direction to go in, that you don't even really have to vote.
You can just look and see what the consensus is and decide what to do.
And so, no, I think it still has to be a leadership position.
And when you get these others, you don't really have the leadership in there that you need.
People don't really feel responsible for it.
And I found this out running the laboratories.
I had to get somebody permanently in charge of them because if you didn't, they just went downhill.
One guy would come in, and he'd be in charge of it, and he wouldn't fix anything because I'm just going to have it this semester.
Somebody else got it after that.
Who were the key people in your departmental office and other staff folks that deserve a pat on the back for their fine work?
Well, actually, Wanda Greer was the one that stayed with me the longest and probably helped me the most.
I used to run through them about one a year until I got a hold of her.
Now, that's the wife of?
John.
She's from Port Arthur, where you are, and knows you.
She did a real good job because she had good judgment.
Mm-hmm.
And also was good at reading anything I wrote and telling me what was wrong.
And she worked with me long enough that she didn't mind telling me when she thought I was wrong and did.
And so that's worth a lot to get somebody that knows the ropes and will just take it and run with it.
All right.
